WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.080 --> 00:00:02.820
Okay, I think we can start. Good afternoon, everybody.

2
00:00:03.400 --> 00:00:07.320
My name is Kamil Krance. I'm a professor of hemato-oncology at the Institute

3
00:00:07.360 --> 00:00:10.680
of Cancer Research in London, and I'll be chairing this session today.

4
00:00:10.740 --> 00:00:12.940
Unfortunately, Dr. Altucci couldn't make it.

5
00:00:13.080 --> 00:00:15.160
She was supposed to chair this session, but she got fever.

6
00:00:15.200 --> 00:00:18.639
She's really apologetic for not being with us here.

7
00:00:19.030 --> 00:00:22.720
So it's a great pleasure to welcome you to the session of Epitranscriptome in

8
00:00:22.800 --> 00:00:26.620
Cancer. The epitranscriptome, the field of RNA modifications, has

9
00:00:26.680 --> 00:00:30.560
emerged over the last few years as a highly promising area in research,

10
00:00:31.280 --> 00:00:35.250
offering opportunities for therapeutic intervention both in solid tumors and

11
00:00:35.300 --> 00:00:39.220
hematological malignancies. To date, over 170

12
00:00:39.800 --> 00:00:43.700
distinct RNA modifications have been identified, affecting multiple

13
00:00:43.800 --> 00:00:47.760
RNA species, including mRNA, tRNA, rRNA, and various

14
00:00:47.840 --> 00:00:48.300
other ones.

15
00:00:49.900 --> 00:00:53.420
However, the biological significance or biological functions of many of these

16
00:00:53.480 --> 00:00:57.230
modifications remain really poorly understood, highlighting

17
00:00:57.280 --> 00:01:00.720
the major challenge and an exciting opportunity.

18
00:01:01.740 --> 00:01:05.520
Typically, RNA modifications are installed by writers, removed by

19
00:01:05.600 --> 00:01:06.540
erasers, and

20
00:01:07.640 --> 00:01:11.420
they are kind of functionally read out by proteins that we call readers.

21
00:01:11.500 --> 00:01:15.360
And the paradigmatic RNA modification, which we call M6A,

22
00:01:15.460 --> 00:01:16.790
which I'll be talking about later,

23
00:01:18.380 --> 00:01:22.060
has already shown immense therapeutic promise, but we still need

24
00:01:22.120 --> 00:01:24.920
to fully understand it. So

25
00:01:26.120 --> 00:01:28.900
M6A writers, readers, and erasers are frequently

26
00:01:29.920 --> 00:01:33.280
upregulated or dysregulated in many cancers, and

27
00:01:34.860 --> 00:01:37.600
the field has already demonstrated that the writers of

28
00:01:38.140 --> 00:01:41.080
methylthree methylases, for example, of M6A,

29
00:01:41.880 --> 00:01:45.720
their inhibitors are already in clinical trials, and the early data

30
00:01:45.730 --> 00:01:49.520
are relatively promising. So we hope that this session will spark

31
00:01:49.540 --> 00:01:51.820
some nice discussion and new collaborators.

32
00:01:51.900 --> 00:01:52.100
And

33
00:01:53.080 --> 00:01:56.860
today we have two speakers, myself and Chu-An Hsueh,

34
00:01:57.000 --> 00:02:00.280
who is a world leader expert in RNA

35
00:02:00.360 --> 00:02:03.960
modifications. So, I will just start by

36
00:02:05.320 --> 00:02:06.860
my own talk, followed by Chu-An.

37
00:02:09.200 --> 00:02:12.940
I'm very grateful to the organizers for inviting us both to

38
00:02:13.380 --> 00:02:16.640
speak here. As I mentioned, my name is Kamil Krance.

39
00:02:16.700 --> 00:02:20.590
I'm based in Institute of Cancer Research in London, and today I'll talk to you

40
00:02:20.620 --> 00:02:24.520
about the functional significance of RNA modifications, focusing on

41
00:02:24.640 --> 00:02:26.760
M6A in blood malignancies.

42
00:02:27.560 --> 00:02:30.760
Acute myeloid leukemia is an aggressive

43
00:02:31.560 --> 00:02:35.300
clonal disease of stem and progenitor cells, which acquire

44
00:02:35.320 --> 00:02:39.020
diverse mutations to generate leukemic stem cells, which fuel leukemia.

45
00:02:39.800 --> 00:02:43.480
Currently available chemotherapies damage normal hematopoiesis,

46
00:02:44.280 --> 00:02:46.760
and they fail to eradicate leukemic stem cells.

47
00:02:47.240 --> 00:02:50.640
Eventually, they cause relapses with severe

48
00:02:50.660 --> 00:02:54.560
consequences to the patients. So my lab, like many other labs

49
00:02:54.620 --> 00:02:58.560
in the world, are trying to address unmet clinical need for non-toxic

50
00:02:58.700 --> 00:03:02.240
cancer stem cell selective treatments, and we hope to pioneer

51
00:03:02.340 --> 00:03:05.780
curative therapies against novel targets we and others have

52
00:03:05.840 --> 00:03:09.540
identified to eradicate leukemic or cancer stem cells in

53
00:03:09.720 --> 00:03:11.540
blood malignancies, including AML.

54
00:03:12.520 --> 00:03:16.140
So it is broadly known that the

55
00:03:16.280 --> 00:03:20.100
strict regulation of gene expression is essential for hematopoietic integrity.

56
00:03:20.140 --> 00:03:23.660
The proper transcription is required for stem cell

57
00:03:23.720 --> 00:03:26.000
maintenance and hematopoietic homeostasis.

58
00:03:27.020 --> 00:03:30.880
However, it has been ignored for many years that multiple RNA species

59
00:03:30.940 --> 00:03:34.880
could undergo chemical modifications, which we refer to as

60
00:03:34.960 --> 00:03:38.880
the epitranscriptome. And the significance of many RNA modifications

61
00:03:38.920 --> 00:03:42.510
in normal and malignant hematopoiesis are really still poorly understood,

62
00:03:42.940 --> 00:03:46.800
obviously giving us the opportunity for brand-new discovery with the potential for

63
00:03:46.820 --> 00:03:50.760
therapeutic development. This is the RNA as we all

64
00:03:50.800 --> 00:03:54.680
know it. It has a coding region flanked by five prime and three

65
00:03:54.780 --> 00:03:58.460
prime UTR. It starts with a cap, finishes with a polytail.

66
00:03:59.060 --> 00:04:03.000
What we do know now, and this is just a very basic schematic, that almost

67
00:04:03.040 --> 00:04:04.380
every part of RNA could

68
00:04:05.740 --> 00:04:07.700
undergo chemical modifications.

69
00:04:08.500 --> 00:04:12.460
My lab has specifically focused on M6A, but also terminal

70
00:04:12.580 --> 00:04:13.660
uridyl transferase

71
00:04:14.720 --> 00:04:18.690
uridylation of the polytail, and for the purpose of this talk, I will fully

72
00:04:18.780 --> 00:04:20.200
focus on M6A.

73
00:04:23.140 --> 00:04:26.960
So M6A is the most abundant internal RNA modification,

74
00:04:27.040 --> 00:04:30.840
which is installed by the enzymes called writers and removed by

75
00:04:31.360 --> 00:04:35.340
erasers. And as we discussed, there are many small molecules now

76
00:04:35.380 --> 00:04:38.700
generated against the writers and erasers, and they seem to have

77
00:04:39.220 --> 00:04:42.930
good therapeutic potential. Some of them are being considered for clinical

78
00:04:43.040 --> 00:04:43.560
trials.

79
00:04:44.360 --> 00:04:48.260
And the M6A is executed by proteins called

80
00:04:48.400 --> 00:04:52.110
readers, which drive RNA decay, translation, or

81
00:04:52.200 --> 00:04:52.690
splicing.

82
00:04:53.600 --> 00:04:56.800
We have specifically focused on three cytosolic readers,

83
00:04:57.320 --> 00:05:01.000
YTHDF2, which promotes RNA decay, and

84
00:05:01.120 --> 00:05:04.210
YTHDF1 and 3 that drive protein translation,

85
00:05:04.940 --> 00:05:08.830
although there's some evidence indicating that

86
00:05:08.840 --> 00:05:12.520
they also might work together to promote RNA decay.

87
00:05:13.160 --> 00:05:16.320
So in my lab we have asked what is the functional significance of

88
00:05:16.420 --> 00:05:19.940
YTHDFs in AML and normal hematopoiesis?

89
00:05:21.060 --> 00:05:24.740
So we found that YTHDF1, 2, and 3 are consistently

90
00:05:24.800 --> 00:05:28.640
overexpressed in acute myeloid leukemia in different subgenetic subtypes

91
00:05:28.680 --> 00:05:32.580
shown here, and YTHDF2 and 3 expression

92
00:05:32.860 --> 00:05:35.180
correlates with the leukemic stem cell activity.

93
00:05:36.800 --> 00:05:40.540
So we have performed genetic dissection of YTHDFs, and I'll show you

94
00:05:41.140 --> 00:05:44.620
some published data and then unpublished data demonstrating this.

95
00:05:45.000 --> 00:05:48.600
To start with, we have focused on YTHDF2 because it's overexpressed quite

96
00:05:48.640 --> 00:05:49.280
consistently

97
00:05:50.320 --> 00:05:52.100
in all leukemias that we have

98
00:05:53.400 --> 00:05:53.800
tested.

99
00:05:54.680 --> 00:05:58.290
Here is the western blot showing that it's consistently overexpressed in acute

100
00:05:58.360 --> 00:06:02.300
myeloid leukemia from typically MLL, AF9, and

101
00:06:02.340 --> 00:06:05.844
P53 mutations.So we asked what

102
00:06:05.924 --> 00:06:09.204
happens if you inhibit or rather knock out

103
00:06:09.364 --> 00:06:13.344
YTHDF2 in human and mouse models? So this is exactly

104
00:06:13.384 --> 00:06:16.804
what we did. It's all published. So I'll just go very quickly through this.

105
00:06:16.884 --> 00:06:20.684
We generated a YTHDF2 knockout mouse, and we took

106
00:06:20.724 --> 00:06:24.494
hematopoietic stem and progenitor cells, transformed them with naturally

107
00:06:24.544 --> 00:06:24.974
occurring

108
00:06:26.124 --> 00:06:29.944
oncogenes, serially replated them, and then transplanted them to mice,

109
00:06:30.624 --> 00:06:34.304
which form leukemia. So even in this in vitro data, you can see in

110
00:06:34.384 --> 00:06:37.804
colony formation assay, which we call CFC, that serial replating

111
00:06:37.864 --> 00:06:41.324
of those YTHDF2 deficient cells

112
00:06:41.804 --> 00:06:45.784
ablates their ability to form leukemic colonies in vitro,

113
00:06:46.244 --> 00:06:50.054
indicating that YTHDF2 deficient cells fail to undergo efficient

114
00:06:50.084 --> 00:06:52.924
transformation regardless which oncogene you use.

115
00:06:55.284 --> 00:06:59.144
And then we transplanted equal numbers of these cells,

116
00:06:59.184 --> 00:07:02.994
and here I'm showing, for example, cells that are transformed with c-Myc and

117
00:07:03.044 --> 00:07:06.624
HOXA9, very powerful oncogenes overexpressed in

118
00:07:06.644 --> 00:07:09.204
40% of AML. We can see that the

119
00:07:09.844 --> 00:07:13.584
YTHDF2 deficient cells really didn't engraft

120
00:07:13.684 --> 00:07:17.364
very well, and YTHDF2 deletion very

121
00:07:17.374 --> 00:07:19.844
significantly extended latency of AML.

122
00:07:20.784 --> 00:07:24.414
And to test the clinical significance of this, we knocked

123
00:07:24.524 --> 00:07:27.824
down YTHDF2 in many-- now I'm showing

124
00:07:27.844 --> 00:07:28.604
three

125
00:07:29.424 --> 00:07:33.324
primary patient samples, and we can see that the knockdown of YTHDF2, not

126
00:07:33.384 --> 00:07:37.324
even full knockdown, almost completely ablated the ability of AML

127
00:07:37.384 --> 00:07:41.184
cells to form colonies in culture, indicating that it's critical for human

128
00:07:41.264 --> 00:07:41.544
AML.

129
00:07:42.704 --> 00:07:46.544
So to understand the molecular mechanisms underlying this, we did RNA sequencing or

130
00:07:46.584 --> 00:07:50.264
gene expression analysis combined with M6A sequencing,

131
00:07:50.684 --> 00:07:54.644
and we really found that the genes that are significantly upregulated

132
00:07:54.704 --> 00:07:58.084
upon YTHDF loss are enriched in M6A

133
00:07:58.124 --> 00:08:01.344
occupancy. So this is exactly what's expected and published by others.

134
00:08:03.344 --> 00:08:06.824
Then we performed the SLAMseq to determine the global RNA

135
00:08:06.844 --> 00:08:10.804
stability assay, and we can see here that the M6A modified

136
00:08:10.844 --> 00:08:11.604
transcripts have

137
00:08:12.783 --> 00:08:16.384
increased stability upon YTHDF deletion.

138
00:08:16.404 --> 00:08:18.864
But performing ribosomal profiling,

139
00:08:19.844 --> 00:08:23.544
we found that the translational efficiency is not affected upon

140
00:08:23.664 --> 00:08:26.624
YTHDF2 deletion, apart from YTHDF2 itself.

141
00:08:27.054 --> 00:08:30.964
So we think that inhibition of YTHDF2 essentially stabilizes

142
00:08:31.024 --> 00:08:32.944
multiple M6A modified transcripts.

143
00:08:33.605 --> 00:08:37.494
And one of those transcripts that we focused on was TNF receptor 2, which is highly

144
00:08:37.564 --> 00:08:41.144
methylated in human and mouse. And to cut the story short,

145
00:08:41.225 --> 00:08:44.834
we essentially demonstrated the way YTHDF2 binds the TNF receptor 2

146
00:08:45.004 --> 00:08:47.384
transcript and results in its degradation.

147
00:08:47.414 --> 00:08:51.184
And if you inhibit or delete, in this case, a TNF receptor 2, which is a

148
00:08:51.264 --> 00:08:54.244
cell surface molecule, then it gets surely

149
00:08:54.564 --> 00:08:58.524
upregulated quite significantly in leukemic cells on the cell

150
00:08:58.604 --> 00:09:02.504
surface. And then we treated those YTHDF knockout cells

151
00:09:02.544 --> 00:09:05.864
with TNF, and we found that they undergo very exuberant

152
00:09:05.904 --> 00:09:09.744
apoptosis. So increased expression of TNF receptor 2

153
00:09:10.184 --> 00:09:14.144
upon YTHDF2 loss could be sensitizing AML cells to

154
00:09:14.284 --> 00:09:17.874
TNF and could form one of the mechanistic insights

155
00:09:18.024 --> 00:09:19.464
why we lose

156
00:09:20.364 --> 00:09:23.624
very quickly YTHDF2 deficient leukemic cells.

157
00:09:24.244 --> 00:09:27.744
So we think that YTHDF2 itself is a therapeutic target in

158
00:09:28.224 --> 00:09:32.104
acute myeloid leukemia, where it allows eradication, a partial at

159
00:09:32.124 --> 00:09:34.024
least eradication of leukemic stem cells.

160
00:09:34.424 --> 00:09:37.884
But if it was to be a therapeutic target, then the question is: what is the impact

161
00:09:37.904 --> 00:09:41.884
on normal hematopoiesis? So that's another question we asked, and

162
00:09:41.924 --> 00:09:44.664
these data are also published, but essentially we

163
00:09:44.704 --> 00:09:47.864
generated a floxed mouse, which is

164
00:09:48.804 --> 00:09:52.604
inducibly deleted by MxCre. So we took these mice, we acutely

165
00:09:52.644 --> 00:09:56.524
deleted YTHDF2 and followed the hematopoiesis in

166
00:09:56.584 --> 00:09:58.324
different lineages. You can see here.

167
00:09:58.904 --> 00:10:01.664
The short story is that acute deletion of

168
00:10:01.764 --> 00:10:05.744
YTHDF2 did not compromise survival or long-term steady state

169
00:10:05.784 --> 00:10:08.124
hematopoiesis. These mice survived beyond

170
00:10:09.064 --> 00:10:13.024
one year and had absolutely no phenotype, apart from one that we noticed.

171
00:10:13.984 --> 00:10:14.244
Here

172
00:10:15.244 --> 00:10:16.784
I'm just showing you very briefly,

173
00:10:18.364 --> 00:10:21.904
expansion of hematopoietic stem cells in multiple different

174
00:10:21.983 --> 00:10:25.024
progenitors. I'm not going into the details. It's published.

175
00:10:25.084 --> 00:10:29.024
We found that it's because of upregulation of pro-inflammatory

176
00:10:29.104 --> 00:10:31.824
signaling going on, but it's not malignant and doesn't really

177
00:10:33.484 --> 00:10:36.914
derail normal hematopoiesis in steady state, but we can discuss it

178
00:10:37.144 --> 00:10:38.974
after the session.

179
00:10:40.564 --> 00:10:44.324
So we think that YTHDF2 is a therapeutic target in acute

180
00:10:44.444 --> 00:10:45.493
myeloid leukemia and

181
00:10:46.464 --> 00:10:50.314
ablating AML, but in a way, really actually at

182
00:10:50.314 --> 00:10:54.124
least in part boosting the hematopoietic stem cell expansion and normal

183
00:10:54.134 --> 00:10:56.804
hematopoiesis, at least in the short term.

184
00:10:58.024 --> 00:11:01.984
So another target that we focused on here is YTHDF3.

185
00:11:02.624 --> 00:11:06.124
It's overexpressed in

186
00:11:06.344 --> 00:11:10.304
different AML subsets, but also its expression correlates with leukemic stem

187
00:11:10.364 --> 00:11:11.124
cell activity.

188
00:11:13.344 --> 00:11:17.264
So in this case, we collaborated with Jacob Hanna in Weizmann Institute, who

189
00:11:17.344 --> 00:11:20.484
gave us the YTHDF3 knockout mice, and we crossed them to

190
00:11:21.104 --> 00:11:22.964
mice which are MLL-AF9

191
00:11:24.104 --> 00:11:27.604
transgenic mice in which the oncogene is induced by doxycycline.

192
00:11:27.664 --> 00:11:31.424
So we performed in vitro and in vivo experiments shown here, and we can see

193
00:11:31.464 --> 00:11:35.384
that deletion of YTHDF3 very significantly

194
00:11:35.424 --> 00:11:38.064
induced apoptosis in leukemic cells.

195
00:11:38.084 --> 00:11:41.984
And when you take these cells and transplant them to mice, essentially what we

196
00:11:42.044 --> 00:11:45.894
can see is that there's a nice delay in leukemogenesis upon deletion of

197
00:11:45.984 --> 00:11:49.904
YTHDF3. So, then we

198
00:11:49.944 --> 00:11:52.084
tested yet another model just to make sure that this

199
00:11:53.844 --> 00:11:57.604
applies to different ones. And in this case, we took

200
00:11:57.704 --> 00:11:59.724
c-Kit positive stem and progenitor cells.

201
00:11:59.764 --> 00:12:02.564
We transformed them with c-Myc and HOXA9 oncogenes,

202
00:12:03.784 --> 00:12:07.344
performed colony assays, and then this was followed by primary

203
00:12:07.384 --> 00:12:08.844
transplantation into recipients.

204
00:12:08.904 --> 00:12:12.684
And we can see that deletion of YTHDF3 ablates the ability

205
00:12:12.744 --> 00:12:16.664
of cells to form leukemic colonies, and upon transplantation, it

206
00:12:16.764 --> 00:12:18.284
delays leukemogenesis in

207
00:12:18.344 --> 00:12:22.208
mice.I don't want to

208
00:12:22.248 --> 00:12:26.108
go into technical details, but we wanted to enumerate leukemic stem

209
00:12:26.168 --> 00:12:29.278
cells, and the gold standard way to do it is to perform limiting

210
00:12:29.808 --> 00:12:33.348
transplantation assays, limiting dilution assays, where you take

211
00:12:33.568 --> 00:12:37.048
different doses of bone marrow cells from YTHDF

212
00:12:37.108 --> 00:12:39.008
control and knockout cells,

213
00:12:39.988 --> 00:12:40.208
and

214
00:12:41.088 --> 00:12:41.168
we

215
00:12:43.628 --> 00:12:46.968
can estimate, using Poisson statistics, the

216
00:12:47.688 --> 00:12:49.168
frequency of leukemic stem cells.

217
00:12:49.208 --> 00:12:53.048
And in this case, we can see that the frequency of leukemic stem

218
00:12:53.058 --> 00:12:56.128
cells in a YTHDF3 deletion is

219
00:12:56.928 --> 00:13:00.768
hugely decreased. So YTHDF3 is essential for leukemic stem

220
00:13:00.828 --> 00:13:01.508
cell maintenance.

221
00:13:02.818 --> 00:13:06.148
Then we knocked down the YTHDF3 expression

222
00:13:07.108 --> 00:13:10.868
in THP-1 cells, with MLL-AF9 translocation.

223
00:13:10.908 --> 00:13:14.568
And sure enough, we found that this induces very significant

224
00:13:14.608 --> 00:13:18.508
apoptosis in THP-1 cells, but various other leukemic human cell

225
00:13:18.568 --> 00:13:20.928
lines, and it slows down the growth.

226
00:13:22.548 --> 00:13:26.508
Then we performed a PDX model using this THP-1 cell line, and we can see

227
00:13:26.548 --> 00:13:30.448
that YTHDF3 knockdown almost completely

228
00:13:30.508 --> 00:13:34.368
ablated the ability here to engraft into the liver, which typically

229
00:13:34.408 --> 00:13:36.328
is very well engrafted

230
00:13:37.268 --> 00:13:39.968
with this particular cell line, and this resulted in an

231
00:13:40.948 --> 00:13:44.408
increase of latency of the

232
00:13:44.568 --> 00:13:48.388
leukemogenesis. So YTHDF3 is essential for human AML cell

233
00:13:48.468 --> 00:13:49.108
engraftment.

234
00:13:50.828 --> 00:13:54.648
And then I talked to clinicians, and we asked, "What is the biggest

235
00:13:54.728 --> 00:13:58.678
problem in our clinic in Royal Marsden Hospital?" And they told me, "P53

236
00:13:58.768 --> 00:14:02.708
mutation." If you have P53 mutation in AML, it's one

237
00:14:02.748 --> 00:14:03.568
of the most poor

238
00:14:03.588 --> 00:14:08.248
prognostic

239
00:14:08.328 --> 00:14:11.968
factor in AML. It's mutated in AML, and it's an

240
00:14:12.008 --> 00:14:14.428
ultra-high risk, therapy-resistant disease.

241
00:14:14.888 --> 00:14:18.628
P53 mutations cause really aggressive, very progressive

242
00:14:18.668 --> 00:14:21.148
disease. So these are very preliminary data.

243
00:14:21.208 --> 00:14:25.128
I'm showing you two patient samples here, but we have done far much more

244
00:14:25.528 --> 00:14:29.008
over the last few days, in fact, and we can see that the knockdown of

245
00:14:29.128 --> 00:14:32.948
YTHDF3 in primary patient samples

246
00:14:32.988 --> 00:14:35.528
decreased the clonogenic capacity

247
00:14:36.408 --> 00:14:40.148
of these colonies in culture. We are now planning to do PDX

248
00:14:40.188 --> 00:14:44.148
models. These are very preliminary data, but I thought I'll share them with you

249
00:14:44.288 --> 00:14:44.528
here.

250
00:14:46.268 --> 00:14:50.008
And then we asked the question, well, what happens really is that

251
00:14:50.408 --> 00:14:54.268
it's very unlikely that one therapy, monotherapy, will treat

252
00:14:54.308 --> 00:14:56.928
AML patients. We probably need to combine them with different

253
00:14:58.788 --> 00:15:01.728
agents. So here we ask the question, what happens if you delete

254
00:15:01.768 --> 00:15:05.668
YTHDF3 and combine it with the current standard

255
00:15:05.748 --> 00:15:08.648
of care, which is Ara-C? And we can see that essentially

256
00:15:08.768 --> 00:15:12.548
YTHDF3 deletion sensitized

257
00:15:12.868 --> 00:15:13.088
to

258
00:15:13.928 --> 00:15:17.708
Ara-C. We can see that the IC50-- Sorry, I switched

259
00:15:17.728 --> 00:15:21.418
those numbers here. I was too keen to show you these data, and I generated this

260
00:15:21.448 --> 00:15:25.188
slide when I was jet lagged. But essentially what I'm trying to say is that IC50

261
00:15:25.248 --> 00:15:28.488
for Ara-C is decreased upon

262
00:15:28.668 --> 00:15:32.348
YTHDF3 deletion. So essentially, an activation of

263
00:15:32.388 --> 00:15:35.608
YTHDF3 sensitizes AML cells to standard of care.

264
00:15:36.648 --> 00:15:39.368
And then we asked the question, is this applicable to any other diseases?

265
00:15:39.408 --> 00:15:43.268
And I don't want to go into major details, but essentially, we focused on multiple

266
00:15:43.308 --> 00:15:46.428
myeloma, which is an incurable disease of plasma cells.

267
00:15:47.048 --> 00:15:50.618
And we took multiple different cell lines in collaboration with our

268
00:15:50.668 --> 00:15:53.188
clinicians in ICR, Charlotte Poland, in this case.

269
00:15:53.248 --> 00:15:53.988
They are diverse

270
00:15:55.748 --> 00:15:59.348
samples of cell lines derived from patients with different

271
00:15:59.388 --> 00:16:02.748
mutations. And what we can see is that regardless of the mutation, regardless of

272
00:16:02.808 --> 00:16:05.068
the cell line, if you knock down YTHDF3,

273
00:16:06.208 --> 00:16:10.068
this compromises multiple

274
00:16:10.548 --> 00:16:12.188
myeloma cell survival.

275
00:16:15.348 --> 00:16:19.138
So then we wanted to understand the impact of YTHDF3 deletion on normal

276
00:16:19.168 --> 00:16:22.858
hematopoiesis, and to cut the long story short, we didn't observe any phenotypes.

277
00:16:22.948 --> 00:16:25.488
We saw no toxicity in normal blood.

278
00:16:25.868 --> 00:16:29.668
We can see that the B cell, T cell, and myeloid

279
00:16:29.748 --> 00:16:32.668
compartment develops very well in the spleen and the bone marrow,

280
00:16:33.608 --> 00:16:36.668
and hematopoietic stem cells are unaffected.

281
00:16:37.048 --> 00:16:39.868
Even we can see expansion of multipotent progenitors.

282
00:16:40.948 --> 00:16:44.048
And then we transplanted hematopoietic stem cells from

283
00:16:44.188 --> 00:16:45.808
YTHDF3 knockout mouse

284
00:16:46.728 --> 00:16:48.608
in primary and secondary recipients.

285
00:16:48.618 --> 00:16:51.428
So in other words, we performed a serial transplantation.

286
00:16:51.488 --> 00:16:54.828
We can see that upon primary transplant, we observed no

287
00:16:54.868 --> 00:16:58.568
differences in the long term. However, if we

288
00:16:58.668 --> 00:17:02.328
sort hematopoietic stem cells from primary recipients and put into secondary

289
00:17:02.348 --> 00:17:06.128
recipients, we begin to see some subtle defects upon YTHDF3

290
00:17:06.168 --> 00:17:09.108
deletion, but that's a very, very long and

291
00:17:09.908 --> 00:17:13.898
stressful experiment. So essentially when you harvest the bone marrow from these

292
00:17:13.969 --> 00:17:17.888
mice, we can still see decent numbers of hematopoietic stem cells in the

293
00:17:18.168 --> 00:17:21.988
recipient mice, really indicating that YTHDF3 is not essential

294
00:17:22.088 --> 00:17:24.008
for hematopoietic stem cell maintenance.

295
00:17:25.588 --> 00:17:28.248
So then we wanted to understand molecular biology behind it.

296
00:17:28.268 --> 00:17:31.628
These are preliminary data we are trying to understand, but essentially we

297
00:17:31.648 --> 00:17:35.308
performed RNA-seq and combined it with m6A sequencing we've done

298
00:17:35.388 --> 00:17:38.918
before. And we found that really loss of YTHDF3 does not

299
00:17:38.968 --> 00:17:41.118
alter, in our case, in leukemic cells,

300
00:17:42.348 --> 00:17:45.348
global levels of m6A modified transcripts.

301
00:17:45.388 --> 00:17:48.688
Then we performed Ribo-seq. I mean, Joan published in the past that

302
00:17:48.848 --> 00:17:52.168
YTHDF3 is controlling protein synthesis.

303
00:17:53.248 --> 00:17:54.108
We are trying to

304
00:17:54.948 --> 00:17:58.668
kind of replicate this, and we are seeing it in leukemic cells in a

305
00:17:58.708 --> 00:18:01.588
slightly subtle way. We have done Ribo-seq here.

306
00:18:01.648 --> 00:18:02.848
We can see that

307
00:18:03.728 --> 00:18:07.588
YTHDF3 deletion subtly compromises translation efficiency of

308
00:18:07.628 --> 00:18:10.908
m6A modified transcripts. These are preliminary data.

309
00:18:10.928 --> 00:18:14.488
We need to improve this, but we did a completely different approach

310
00:18:14.588 --> 00:18:18.548
now. We performed transcriptome in these cells and

311
00:18:18.748 --> 00:18:22.668
together with proteome that we have done recently, and we combined them

312
00:18:22.688 --> 00:18:26.208
in different clusters, and we have focused on two clusters, the bottom ones

313
00:18:26.308 --> 00:18:29.892
hereWhere transcripts are either unaffected or going down

314
00:18:30.232 --> 00:18:33.692
upon YTHDF3 deletion, but the proteins are

315
00:18:34.112 --> 00:18:38.032
really down-regulated. And then when we performed a GO analysis, a very

316
00:18:38.132 --> 00:18:41.162
other functional analysis, what we are seeing is cytosolic translation,

317
00:18:41.812 --> 00:18:45.211
mitochondrial translation, ribosomal biogenesis.

318
00:18:45.272 --> 00:18:48.512
So it was quite striking. We still don't understand exactly what's going on,

319
00:18:48.612 --> 00:18:52.482
whether it's translation, ribosomal assembly, biogenesis, we don't

320
00:18:52.512 --> 00:18:56.372
know. But basically what we are seeing is that upon YTHDF3

321
00:18:56.412 --> 00:18:59.492
deletion, a lot of M6A transcripts and

322
00:18:59.532 --> 00:19:03.172
proteins are down-regulated, and these are the ones that are

323
00:19:03.212 --> 00:19:05.592
normally up-regulated in leukemic stem cells.

324
00:19:07.392 --> 00:19:10.192
So then we asked the question: what happens in multiple myeloma?

325
00:19:10.312 --> 00:19:13.672
I don't have time to go into the details, but we performed essentially very similar

326
00:19:13.712 --> 00:19:17.312
clustering where we found a lot of proteins being down-regulated.

327
00:19:17.342 --> 00:19:20.922
And the GO analysis, again, indicated in a completely different disease,

328
00:19:21.332 --> 00:19:25.152
cytosolic translation, cytoplasmic translation initiation,

329
00:19:25.292 --> 00:19:27.672
mRNA processing. And you can see here,

330
00:19:28.572 --> 00:19:32.372
diverse proteins being down-regulated

331
00:19:32.692 --> 00:19:35.092
upon YTHDF3 knockdown here

332
00:19:36.032 --> 00:19:39.612
in myeloma cells, and they all belong to RNA processing

333
00:19:40.112 --> 00:19:40.532
pathway.

334
00:19:41.772 --> 00:19:45.712
So then we asked, well, can we actually a little bit more functionally validate it?

335
00:19:45.752 --> 00:19:49.152
It's so brand new to me and our lab, so we are learning all these technologies.

336
00:19:49.172 --> 00:19:52.372
We collaborated with various people at ICR who know better how to do it.

337
00:19:52.412 --> 00:19:56.072
And essentially what we found is that both in mouse AML cells and

338
00:19:56.152 --> 00:20:00.052
human AML cells with the knockdown or knockout of YTHDF3, we can see

339
00:20:00.072 --> 00:20:02.532
a polysome defect here. Here, those

340
00:20:03.792 --> 00:20:07.532
peaks I'm showing you here, they are heavy polysomes, and we can see that they

341
00:20:08.232 --> 00:20:10.752
fail to assemble efficiently or translate

342
00:20:13.452 --> 00:20:16.952
into proteins. So then we kind of fractionated those

343
00:20:17.332 --> 00:20:20.452
polysomes. Again, these are preliminary data, but we can see that those large

344
00:20:20.552 --> 00:20:22.152
polysomes that seem to be defected

345
00:20:23.492 --> 00:20:26.392
in the absence of YTHDF3, they fail to

346
00:20:27.392 --> 00:20:31.352
efficiently translate M6A transcripts, at least the

347
00:20:31.412 --> 00:20:33.632
selected transcripts I'm showing you here.

348
00:20:33.692 --> 00:20:35.332
There's much more to be done to prove

349
00:20:35.372 --> 00:20:39.292
it better.

350
00:20:39.372 --> 00:20:43.172
So we think that YTHDF3 inactivation compromises AML

351
00:20:43.212 --> 00:20:45.372
by affecting ribosomal function

352
00:20:46.852 --> 00:20:48.932
or ribosomal assembly or biogenesis.

353
00:20:48.992 --> 00:20:52.572
We are still trying to find a distinction here, but whatever you do,

354
00:20:52.712 --> 00:20:56.652
or whatever happens, YTHDF3 inhibition or

355
00:20:56.692 --> 00:21:00.522
inactivation compromises leukemia but has no impact on

356
00:21:00.552 --> 00:21:01.672
normal hematopoiesis.

357
00:21:05.692 --> 00:21:08.752
Then we ask the question: well, what happens if you inhibit

358
00:21:09.592 --> 00:21:13.512
YTHDF3 and YTHDF1? YTHDF1 is also shown

359
00:21:13.532 --> 00:21:17.372
to promote protein translation, so we generated the double

360
00:21:17.452 --> 00:21:18.232
mutant cells.

361
00:21:19.172 --> 00:21:23.152
Here I'm just showing you that YTHDF1 is required for leukemogenesis

362
00:21:23.792 --> 00:21:27.352
upon MLL transformation just the same way that YTHDF3 is

363
00:21:27.472 --> 00:21:31.252
required. But then we generated double knockout mice where they

364
00:21:31.312 --> 00:21:35.132
lack YTHDF1 and 3, and we can clearly see that there's very

365
00:21:35.172 --> 00:21:36.201
little going on in these--

366
00:21:37.092 --> 00:21:40.722
sorry. What I'm trying to say is that if you knock out YTHDF1,

367
00:21:41.392 --> 00:21:44.312
3, or both, there's no synergistic effect

368
00:21:44.372 --> 00:21:48.152
here. For instance, here we can see a Kaplan-Meier curve

369
00:21:48.272 --> 00:21:50.562
with mice injected with wild type cells.

370
00:21:50.632 --> 00:21:52.572
They really die from leukemia pretty fast.

371
00:21:53.092 --> 00:21:56.992
But if you delete YTHDF1, 3, or both, there's somehow

372
00:21:57.072 --> 00:22:00.132
no exacerbation of this anti-leukemic effect.

373
00:22:01.712 --> 00:22:05.582
Importantly, we looked at normal hematopoiesis in these mice, and

374
00:22:05.632 --> 00:22:09.472
to cut the long story short, there was a pretty normal

375
00:22:09.652 --> 00:22:13.592
multi-lineage hematopoiesis. We even noticed that hematopoietic stem

376
00:22:13.652 --> 00:22:17.552
cells were in fact expanded upon mutation of 1 and 3

377
00:22:17.612 --> 00:22:21.602
paralogs. Then we performed a transplantation assay, and

378
00:22:21.612 --> 00:22:25.372
again, what we found is that combined

379
00:22:25.412 --> 00:22:29.102
deletion of YTHDF1 and 3 does not affect the ability of

380
00:22:29.132 --> 00:22:32.452
hematopoietic stem cells to reconstitute multi-lineage hematopoiesis.

381
00:22:33.292 --> 00:22:37.212
So we think that YTHDF3 in this case is a good therapeutic target,

382
00:22:37.872 --> 00:22:41.652
but inhibition of both of them, if we had a drug, for example, that inhibits both

383
00:22:41.692 --> 00:22:44.331
of them, will not have any toxicity against

384
00:22:45.692 --> 00:22:46.831
normal hematopoiesis.

385
00:22:50.952 --> 00:22:53.151
So then we ask the question: well, what happens if you

386
00:22:54.172 --> 00:22:58.052
delete YTHDF1 and 3? They are both very highly overexpressed in

387
00:22:58.092 --> 00:22:58.632
leukemia.

388
00:22:59.892 --> 00:23:03.212
So here what we found is that if you knock down YTHDF1

389
00:23:03.792 --> 00:23:06.652
or 2, you obviously have down-regulation of

390
00:23:07.472 --> 00:23:11.152
growth. But if you knock down both of them, there's a very severe

391
00:23:11.162 --> 00:23:12.692
defect and very

392
00:23:13.512 --> 00:23:16.612
strong pro-apoptotic effect upon knockdown of

393
00:23:16.712 --> 00:23:18.292
YTHDF1 and 2.

394
00:23:20.472 --> 00:23:24.392
So we generated mice that lack YTHDF1

395
00:23:24.412 --> 00:23:26.172
and 2. Sorry, there are some

396
00:23:27.332 --> 00:23:31.152
labels that are missing here. But what I'm trying to show here is that if you

397
00:23:31.252 --> 00:23:33.492
delete YTHDF1 and 2,

398
00:23:34.492 --> 00:23:38.052
you get almost complete ablation of leukemogenesis in vitro.

399
00:23:38.872 --> 00:23:42.712
And if you manage to grow enough cells and perform

400
00:23:42.752 --> 00:23:46.612
transplantation with them, there's a complete ablation of ability

401
00:23:46.672 --> 00:23:49.892
of these cells to generate leukemia if you delete both

402
00:23:50.032 --> 00:23:51.572
YTHDF1 and 2.

403
00:23:53.152 --> 00:23:54.412
So I showed you that

404
00:23:55.432 --> 00:23:57.592
YTHDF2 recognizes

405
00:23:57.672 --> 00:24:00.952
M6A-modified TNF receptor 2.

406
00:24:01.952 --> 00:24:05.762
When you delete 1 or 2, TNF receptor 2 goes up,

407
00:24:05.992 --> 00:24:09.772
but if you delete YTHDF1 and 2 together, it seems like

408
00:24:09.832 --> 00:24:12.392
there's an additive effect. So perhaps

409
00:24:13.572 --> 00:24:17.442
a loss of YTHDF1 and 2 is sufficient to up-regulate TNF receptor, and

410
00:24:17.812 --> 00:24:21.722
1 and 2 are possibly likely acting together to repress this

411
00:24:21.772 --> 00:24:24.592
locus. In this case, they might have some overlapping functions.

412
00:24:26.012 --> 00:24:28.572
So we think that the deletion of YTHDF1 and 2

413
00:24:29.492 --> 00:24:33.320
has very strong anti-leukemic effect, almost curative.And

414
00:24:34.260 --> 00:24:37.000
the question is: does it affect normal hematopoiesis?

415
00:24:38.200 --> 00:24:39.820
So these are very preliminary data.

416
00:24:39.860 --> 00:24:43.440
We generated wild-type cells, and at the end of all these graphs, you can see

417
00:24:43.480 --> 00:24:47.320
double knockout cells, double knockout mice that lack YTHDF1

418
00:24:47.340 --> 00:24:51.020
and 2 inducibly. And to cut the long story

419
00:24:51.100 --> 00:24:55.000
short, these mice don't develop any severe defects as we kind

420
00:24:55.060 --> 00:24:55.800
of expected.

421
00:24:56.640 --> 00:25:00.510
Some people probably even said that it would be very lethal, but

422
00:25:00.580 --> 00:25:01.420
we didn't notice that.

423
00:25:03.240 --> 00:25:06.320
What we see is that these mice have normal red blood cells, normal

424
00:25:06.760 --> 00:25:10.240
platelets. They have normal multilineage steady-state

425
00:25:10.280 --> 00:25:11.240
hematopoiesis.

426
00:25:13.680 --> 00:25:15.900
And then we looked at hematopoietic stem cells, and

427
00:25:16.840 --> 00:25:18.600
one would have expected they would be gone.

428
00:25:18.780 --> 00:25:20.960
Actually, they are still there, and they are performing quite well.

429
00:25:21.500 --> 00:25:24.620
So the entire hematopoietic hierarchy is

430
00:25:24.880 --> 00:25:28.220
unperturbed upon deletion of YTHDF1 and 2

431
00:25:28.260 --> 00:25:29.020
genetically.

432
00:25:29.980 --> 00:25:33.480
So we think that deletion or inhibition of YTHDF1 and 2

433
00:25:33.880 --> 00:25:37.780
could also function as a good therapeutic target where you ablate

434
00:25:37.800 --> 00:25:40.460
leukemia but preserve normal hematopoiesis.

435
00:25:42.420 --> 00:25:46.020
So are YTHDFs redundant? Can we substitute one

436
00:25:46.060 --> 00:25:49.480
another? I think it's very, very complex and context specific, and

437
00:25:50.200 --> 00:25:53.010
we are not in a position to get into this dispute.

438
00:25:53.630 --> 00:25:56.160
But what we did was to try to replace

439
00:25:56.240 --> 00:26:00.100
YTHDF1 with 2. So essentially what we did

440
00:26:00.620 --> 00:26:03.720
was to knock in YTHDF1

441
00:26:04.540 --> 00:26:08.410
into the locus of YTHDF2 and ask the question, can we at least in

442
00:26:08.480 --> 00:26:11.820
part rescue some phenotypes? And indeed, it was the case, at least in

443
00:26:11.860 --> 00:26:14.900
hematopoiesis, but not necessarily in leukemia.

444
00:26:16.100 --> 00:26:19.390
So if you remember from the beginning of my talk, I showed that

445
00:26:19.520 --> 00:26:23.120
YTHDF2 knockout expanded hematopoietic stem cells.

446
00:26:23.180 --> 00:26:25.550
And what I'm showing here is that those stem cells,

447
00:26:26.620 --> 00:26:30.040
with this knock-in model are no longer expanded, and the multiple

448
00:26:30.140 --> 00:26:33.740
progenitor cells are also not expanded, indicating that

449
00:26:33.920 --> 00:26:37.260
the YTHDF1 can substitute for

450
00:26:37.300 --> 00:26:40.580
YTHDF2 functionally, at least in normal hematopoiesis.

451
00:26:41.020 --> 00:26:45.000
I don't have the leukemia data to show here, but in leukemia, we didn't see

452
00:26:45.020 --> 00:26:45.260
that.

453
00:26:47.380 --> 00:26:50.480
So is targeting the YTHDF domain

454
00:26:51.280 --> 00:26:53.660
sufficient to inactivate YTHDF2?

455
00:26:53.700 --> 00:26:54.500
How do we actually

456
00:26:55.600 --> 00:26:58.600
go about it? How do we inhibit YTHDF2 therapeutically?

457
00:26:59.280 --> 00:27:02.400
So as you can see here, the C terminus of

458
00:27:02.480 --> 00:27:06.200
YTHDF2 and other YTHDFs have three conserved

459
00:27:06.220 --> 00:27:09.880
tryptophans, and every single each of them is required for M6A

460
00:27:09.960 --> 00:27:13.560
binding. So we ask the question, what happens if you mutagenize one of them, the

461
00:27:13.600 --> 00:27:17.440
final one? And here is the structure of a wild-type YTHDF2

462
00:27:18.080 --> 00:27:21.860
embracing the M6A. And if you delete or substitute

463
00:27:22.040 --> 00:27:25.980
one tryptophan into alanine, the M6A binding

464
00:27:26.020 --> 00:27:29.740
is hugely decreased. So we made that mouse by CRISPR-Cas9

465
00:27:29.760 --> 00:27:33.289
together with Donald O'Carroll in Edinburgh, and we asked the question:

466
00:27:33.680 --> 00:27:35.960
what happens to normal and malignant hematopoiesis?

467
00:27:36.360 --> 00:27:39.560
What is the impact of this genetic disruption of this

468
00:27:39.680 --> 00:27:43.220
YTHDF2 M6A binding in normal and malignant hematopoiesis?

469
00:27:43.740 --> 00:27:47.540
So to cut a long story short, we generated wild-type mice, knockout

470
00:27:47.600 --> 00:27:51.140
mice for YTHDF2, and those that we call WA, which is the

471
00:27:51.220 --> 00:27:53.240
tryptophan to alanine substitution.

472
00:27:53.740 --> 00:27:57.100
And essentially what we found is that these mice are born.

473
00:27:57.190 --> 00:27:57.460
They are

474
00:27:58.280 --> 00:28:01.380
pretty happy, but the WA mutation does

475
00:28:01.440 --> 00:28:04.840
recapitulate the stem cell expansion upon knockout.

476
00:28:04.970 --> 00:28:08.750
And importantly, in various other

477
00:28:08.780 --> 00:28:11.600
compartments, we see the same. For example, the WA

478
00:28:11.800 --> 00:28:15.380
mutation still displays the expansion of multipotent

479
00:28:15.440 --> 00:28:18.180
progenitors that we do also observed in the knockout mice.

480
00:28:18.800 --> 00:28:22.700
So that indicates that YTHDF2 function in normal hematopoiesis is

481
00:28:22.740 --> 00:28:24.560
dependent on M6A binding.

482
00:28:25.970 --> 00:28:29.820
Then we crossed these WA mice to the MLL-translocated mice that are

483
00:28:29.840 --> 00:28:32.900
leukemic, and we performed colony assays.

484
00:28:32.940 --> 00:28:36.010
And you can clearly see just in vitro data that if you just

485
00:28:36.700 --> 00:28:40.660
introduce that one point mutation, you ablate the ability

486
00:28:40.760 --> 00:28:44.260
of leukemic cells or pre-leukemic cells to form leukemia.

487
00:28:44.320 --> 00:28:47.140
They basically fail to proliferate, and they die.

488
00:28:48.580 --> 00:28:52.360
